    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:768d956d-0675-42ca-b7ba-23fb2d868f18",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 38-year-old Czech woman with a slender build and a visibly fatigued, unwell appearance. She presents with a persistent productive cough with discoloured sputum, progressive dyspnea on exertion, nasal congestion, low-grade fever, drenching night sweats, and unintentional weight loss of approximately 6 kg over the past two months. She also reports intermittent stomach discomfort and early satiety. On examination she appears pale and mildly diaphoretic, with palpable cervical and axillary lymphadenopathy, and oxygen saturation mildly reduced at rest.\n\n{patientName} works part-time as a librarian in Brno, a role that involves regular contact with the public, volunteers from community outreach programmes, and occasional student groups visiting from abroad — including exchange visitors from regions with higher TB prevalence. She lives with her younger sister and sister's family in a small, somewhat crowded apartment. She enjoys reading, attending small theatre performances, and weekend hiking. However, her progressive fatigue, cough, and breathlessness have significantly curtailed outdoor activities over recent weeks.\n\nShe does not smoke and denies intravenous drug use. She drinks alcohol occasionally (wine on social occasions). She disclosed to her infectious disease physician that her HIV infection was acquired through unprotected heterosexual intercourse with a partner whose HIV status she later learned was positive — a recognised transmission risk behaviour. In the period before her HIV diagnosis she had multiple sexual partners and inconsistently used barrier contraception, which she now acknowledges as a key risk factor in her history.\n\nShe has a close circle of friends but has noted increased social withdrawal due to her symptoms and the stigma she fears regarding her HIV status, which she has not disclosed to most acquaintances. She is not currently in a relationship. She maintains contact with her mother and maternal grandmother, both living in Ostrava. Her mother is also living with HIV, which has affected the family's awareness of — and anxiety around — immune-related illness."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:2934ec25-b8c6-4b7d-bde3-46bea09495fb",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} was diagnosed with HIV infection three years ago following a routine screening prompted by a new relationship disclosure. She was linked to infectious disease care at Fakultní nemocnice Brno but has had irregular follow-up in the past year, resulting in a lapse in antiretroviral therapy adherence. Approximately eighteen months ago she experienced a milder episode of persistent cough, low-grade fever, and significant fatigue lasting several weeks, which resolved partially without formal investigation — in retrospect, this likely represented an earlier, less severe opportunistic respiratory infection and may represent a prior similar episode of immune compromise. She has a known history of mild iron-deficiency anaemia, for which she takes ferrous sulfate supplementation. She also suffers from seasonal allergic rhinitis managed with cetirizine, and she experienced a prior episode of bronchospasm attributed to allergic sensitisation, using salbutamol inhaler as needed. Omeprazole was initiated for dyspeptic symptoms related to iron supplementation, and folic acid is taken as a nutritional supplement.\n\nShe has no prior confirmed diagnosis of tuberculosis, though she travelled to Ukraine and Romania in the past two years, both countries with elevated TB burden, providing an epidemiological exposure risk. Her occupation as a librarian, while not a traditional high-risk setting, involves regular close contact with diverse community members including visitors from high-prevalence regions, providing community-level TB exposure. She has no prior surgical history apart from a lymph node biopsy performed in 2023 to evaluate cervical lymphadenopathy, which was non-diagnostic at the time. She has never been hospitalised for infectious complications until the current presentation. She is a non-smoker and does not use intravenous drugs. Her HIV acquisition was through unprotected heterosexual intercourse — a documented lifestyle risk factor for HIV transmission prior to her diagnosis."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
